1036
1037 /*
1038 There are three kinds of conditions stored into a table's QEP_TAB object:
1039
1040 1. Join conditions (where not optimized into EQ_REF accesses or similar).
1041 These are attached as a condition on the rightmost table of the join;
1042 if it's an outer join, they are wrapped in a not_null_compl
1043 condition, to mark that they should not be applied to the NULL values
1044 synthesized when no row is found. These can be kept on the table, and
1045 we don't really need the not_null_compl wrapper as long as we don't
1046 move the condition up above the join (which we don't).
1047
1048 2. WHERE predicates referring to the table, and possibly also one or more
1049 earlier tables in the join. These should normally be kept on the table,
1050 so we can discard rows as early as possible (but see next point).
1051 We should test these after the join conditions, though, as they may
1052 have side effects. Also note that these may be pushed below sort
1053 operations for efficiency -- in fact, they already have, so we should
1054 not try to re-apply them.
1055
1056 3. Predicates like in #2 that are on the inner (right) side of a
1057 left join. These conditions must be moved _above_ the join, as they
1058 should also be tested for NULL-complemented rows the join may generate.
1059 E.g., for t1 LEFT JOIN t2 WHERE t1.x + t2.x > 3, the condition will be
1060 attached to t2's QEP_TAB, but needs to be attached above the join, or
1061 it would erroneously keep rows wherever t2 did not produce a
1062 (real) row. Such conditions are marked with a found trigger (in the
1063 old execution engine, which tested qep_tab->condition() both before and
1064 after the join, it would need to be exempt from the first test).
1065
1066 4. Predicates that are #1 _and_ #3. These can happen with more complicated
1067 outer joins; e.g., with t1 LEFT JOIN ( t2 LEFT JOIN t3 ON <x> ) ON <y>,
1068 the <x> join condition (posted on t3) should be above one join but
1069 below the other.
1070
1071 Special case:
1072 If we are on the inner side of a semijoin with only one table, any
1073 condition attached to this table is lifted up to where the semijoin
1074 iterator would be created. If we have more than one table on the inner
1075 side of a semijoin, and if conditions attached to these tables are
1076 lifted up to the semijoin iterator, we do not create good plans.
1077 Therefore, for such a case, we take special care to try and attach
1078 the condition to the correct hash join iterator. To do the same, we
1079 find if the fields in a join condition are available within the join
1080 created for the current table. If the fields are available, we attach the
1081 condition to the hash join iterator created for the current table.
1082 We make use of "semi_join_table_idx" to know where the semijoin iterator
1083 would be created and "left_tables" to know the tables that are available
1084 for the join that will be created for the current table.
1085 Note that, as of now, for mysql, we do not enable join buffering thereby
1086 not enabling hash joins when a semijoin has more than one table on
1087 its inner side. However, we enable it for secondary engines.
1088
1089 TODO: The optimizer should distinguish between before-join and
1090 after-join conditions to begin with, instead of us having to untangle
1091 it here.
1092 */

1283 /**
1284 Given a range of tables (where we assume that we've already handled
1285 first_idx..(this_idx-1) as inner joins), figure out whether this is a
1286 semijoin, an outer join or a weedout. In general, the outermost structure
1287 wins; if we are in one of the rare cases where there are e.g. coincident
1288 (first match) semijoins and weedouts, we do various forms of conflict
1289 resolution:
1290
1291 - Unhandled weedouts will add elements to unhandled_duplicates
1292 (to be handled at the top level of the query).

1294 * Set add_limit_1 to true, which means a LIMIT 1 iterator should

1297 be solved by a simple one-table, one-row LIMIT.

1323 // Outer joins (or semijoins) wrapping a weedout is tricky,
1324 // especially in edge cases. If we have an outer join wrapping
1325 // a weedout, the outer join needs to be processed first.
1326 // But the weedout wins if it's strictly larger than the outer join.
1327 // However, a problem occurs if the weedout wraps two consecutive
1328 // outer joins (which can happen if the join optimizer interleaves
1329 // tables from different weedouts and needs to combine them into
1330 // one larger weedout). E.g., consider a join order such as
1331 //
1332 // a LEFT JOIN (b,c) LEFT JOIN (d,e)
1333 //
1334 // where there is _also_ a weedout wrapping all four tables [b,e].
1335 // (Presumably, there were originally two weedouts b+e and c+d,
1336 // but due to reordering, they were combined into one.)
1337 // In this case, we have a non-hierarchical situation since the
1338 // (a,(b,c)) join only partially overlaps with the [b,e] weedout.
1339 //
1340 // We solve these non-hierarchical cases by punting them upwards;
1341 // we signal that they are simply not done by adding them to
1342 // unhandled_duplicates, and then drop the weedout. The top level
1343 // will then add a final weedout after all joins. In some cases,
1344 // it is possible to push the weedout further down than this,
1345 // but these cases are so marginal that it's not worth it.

1883 // Create a hash join iterator with the given build and probe input. We will
1884 // move conditions from the argument "join_conditions" into two separate lists;
1885 // one list for equi-join conditions that will be used as normal join conditions
1886 // in hash join, and one list for non-equi-join conditions that will be attached
1887 // as "extra" conditions in hash join. The "extra" conditions are conditions
1888 // that must be evaluated after the hash table lookup, but _before_ returning a
1889 // row. Conditions that are not moved will be attached as filters after the
1890 // join. Note that we only attach conditions as "extra" conditions if the join
1891 // type is not inner join. This gives us more fine-grained output from EXPLAIN
1892 // ANALYZE, where we can see whether the condition was expensive.
1893 // This information is lost when we attach conditions as extra conditions inside
1894 // hash join.
1895 //
1896 // The function will also determine whether hash join is allowed to spill to
1897 // disk. In general, we reject spill to disk if the query has a LIMIT and no
1898 // aggregation or grouping. See comments inside the function for justification.

2233 /**
2234 For a given slice of the table list, build up the iterator tree corresponding
2235 to the tables in that slice. It handles inner and outer joins, as well as
2236 semijoins (first match).
2237
2238 The join tree in MySQL is generally a left-deep tree of inner joins,
2239 so we can start at the left, make an inner join against the next table,
2240 join the result of that against the next table, etc.. However, a given
2241 sub-slice of the table list can be designated as an outer join, by setting
2242 first_inner() and last_inner() on the first table of said slice. (It is also
2243 set in some, but not all, of the other tables in the slice.) If so, we call
2244 ourselves recursively with that slice, put it as the right (inner) arm of
2245 an outer join, and then continue with our inner join.
2246
2247 Similarly, if a table N has set first match to table M (ie., jump back to
2248 table M whenever we see a non-filtered record in table N), then there is a
2249 subslice from [M+1,N] that we need to process recursively before putting it
2250 as the right side of a semijoin. Every semijoin can be implemented with a
2251 LIMIT 1, but for clarity and performance, we prefer to use a NestedLoopJoin
2252 with a special SEMI join type whenever possible. Sometimes, we have no choice,
2253 though (see the comments below). Note that we cannot use first_sj_inner() for
2254 detecting semijoins, as it is not updated when tables are reordered by the
2255 join optimizer. Outer joins and semijoins can nest, so we need to take some
2256 care to make sure that we pick the outermost structure to recurse on.
2257
2258 Conditions are a bit tricky. Conceptually, SQL evaluates conditions only
2259 after all tables have been joined; however, for efficiency reasons, we want
2260 to evaluate them as early as possible. As long as we are only dealing with
2261 inner joins, this is as soon as we've read all tables participating in the
2262 condition, but for outer joins, we need to wait until the join has happened.
2263 See pending_conditions below.
2264
2265 @param upper_first_idx gives us the first table index of the other side of the
2266 join. Only valid if we are inside a substructure (outer join, semijoin or
2267 antijoin). I.e., if we are processing the right side of the query
2268 't1 LEFT JOIN t2', upper_first_idx gives us the table index of 't1'. Used by
2269 hash join to determine the table map for each side of the join.
2270 @param first_idx index of the first table in the slice we are creating a
2271 tree for (inclusive)
2272 @param last_idx index of the last table in the slice we are creating a
2273 tree for (exclusive)
2274 @param qep_tabs the full list of tables we are joining
2275 @param thd the THD to allocate the iterators on
2276 @param calling_context what situation we have immediately around is in the
2277 tree (ie., whether we are called to resolve the inner part of an outer
2278 join, a semijoin, etc.); mostly used to avoid infinite recursion where we
2279 would process e.g. the same semijoin over and over again
2280 @param pending_conditions if nullptr, we are not at the right (inner) side of
2281 any outer join and can evaluate conditions immediately. If not, we need to
2282 push any WHERE predicates to that vector and evaluate them only after joins.
2283 @param pending_invalidators a global list of CacheInvalidatorIterators we
2284 need to emit, but cannot yet due to pending outer joins. Note that unlike
2285 pending_conditions and pending_join_conditions, this is never nullptr,
2286 and is always the same pointer when recursing within the same JOIN.
2287 @param pending_join_conditions if not nullptr, we are at the inner side of
2288 semijoin/antijoin. The join iterator is created at the outer side, so any
2289 join conditions at the inner side needs to be pushed to this vector so that
2290 they can be attached to the join iterator. Note that this is currently only
2291 used by hash join.
2292 @param[out] unhandled_duplicates list of tables we should have deduplicated
2293 using duplicate weedout, but could not; append-only.
2294 @param[out] conditions_depend_on_outer_tables For each condition we have
2295 applied on the inside of these iterators, their dependent tables are
2296 appended to this set. Thus, if conditions_depend_on_outer_tables contain
2297 something from outside the tables covered by [first_idx,last_idx)
2298 (ie., after translation from QEP_TAB indexes to table indexes), we cannot
2299 use a hash join, since the returned iterator depends on seeing outer rows
2300 when evaluating its conditions.
2301 */
2302 2263943 AccessPath *ConnectJoins(plan_idx upper_first_idx, plan_idx first_idx,

2304 CallingContext calling_context,

2309 table_map *conditions_depend_on_outer_tables) {

3721 /*
3722 If we have an item like <expr> IN ( SELECT f2 FROM t2 ), and we were not
3723 able to rewrite it into a semijoin, the optimizer may rewrite it into
3724 EXISTS ( SELECT 1 FROM t2 WHERE f2=<expr> LIMIT 1 ) (ie., pushing down the
3725 value into the subquery), using a REF or REF_OR_NULL scan on t2 if possible.
3726 This happens in Item_in_subselect::select_in_like_transformer() and the
3727 functions it calls.
3728
3729 However, if <expr> evaluates to NULL, this transformation is incorrect,
3730 and the transformation used should instead be to
3731
3732 EXISTS ( SELECT 1 FROM t2 LIMIT 1 ) ? NULL : FALSE.
3733
3734 Thus, in the case of nullable <expr>, the rewriter inserts so-called
3735 condition guards (pointers to bool saying whether <expr> was NULL or not,
3736 for each part of <expr> if it contains multiple columns). These condition
3737 guards do two things:
3738
3739 1. They disable the pushed-down WHERE clauses.
3740 2. They change the REF/REF_OR_NULL accesses to table scans.
3741
3742 We don't need to worry about #1 here, but #2 needs to be dealt with,
3743 as it changes the plan. We solve it by inserting an AlternativeIterator
3744 that chooses between two sub-iterators at execution time, based on the
3745 condition guard in question.
3746
3747 Note that ideally, we'd plan a completely separate plan for the NULL case,
3748 as there might be e.g. a different index we could scan on, or even a
3749 different optimal join order. (Note, however, that for the case of multiple
3750 columns in the expression, we could get 2^N different plans.) However, given
3751 that most cases are now handled by semijoins and not in2exists at all,
3752 we don't need to jump through every possible hoop to optimize these cases.
3753 */
3754
2/2
✓ Branch 0 taken 1935359 times.
✓ Branch 1 taken 1828462 times.

3755
2/2
✓ Branch 0 taken 2364930 times.
✓ Branch 1 taken 1934738 times.

3756 ++key_part_idx) {
3757
2/2
✓ Branch 0 taken 621 times.
✓ Branch 1 taken 2364309 times.

3758 // At least one condition guard is relevant, so we need to use

4376 i==3 -> afe-3-1 == 6 i==9 -> 9-4 == 5

4384
4385 fields (selected_fields)
4386 | |

4389 |0 | -> |1 | -> |2 | -> |3 | -> |4 |
4390 +--+ +--+ +--+ +--+ +--+

4397 (visible) elements == 3 added_non_hidden_fields == 2
4398 orig_num_select_elements == 1

4401
4402 +---#---+---+
4403 | 2 # 1 | 0 | ref_item_array
4404 +---#---+---+

4497 /**
4498 Set all column values from all input tables to NULL.
4499
4500 This is used when no rows are found during grouping: for FROM clause, a
4501 result row of all NULL values will be output; then SELECT list expressions
4502 get evaluated. E.g. SUM() will be NULL (the special "clear" value) and thus
4503 SUM() IS NULL will be true.
